'''Hilary Dwyer''' (born 6 May 1945, [[Liverpool]]) is a former [[actress]], [[businessperson]] and [[film producer]].
==Early life== Dwyer is the daughter of an Orthopaedic Surgeon. As a youth, she practiced ballet and became a talented pianist.<ref>[http://deadline.theavengers.tv/murderv1.htm The Avengers-Press Releases]</ref> Dwyer trained in [[repertory theatre]]s and appeared on stage at the [[Bristol Old Vic]].
==Acting career== Dwyer is best known for appearing in several [[horror film]]s distributed by [[American International Pictures]] in the late 1960s and early 1970s, most notably [[Michael Reeves]]' ''[[Witchfinder General (film)|Witchfinder General]]'' (1968), starring [[Vincent Price]]. She also appeared in ''[[The Oblong Box (film)|The Oblong Box]]'' (1969) and ''[[Cry of the Banshee]]'' (1970), both again featuring Price, as well as [[Robert Fuest]]'s [[Wuthering Heights (1970 film)|''Wuthering Heights'']] (1970). ''Banshee'' was her final feature film appearance, and after that she worked only in television. Her many television roles included ''[[The Prisoner]]'', ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'', ''[[Hadleigh (TV series)|Hadleigh]]'' and ''[[Van der Valk (TV series)|Van der Valk]]''. Her last credit as an actress was in 1976, in a small part in an episode of ''[[Space: 1999]]''.<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0245495/bio Hilary Heath at imdb.com] Retrieved 29 August 2010</ref>
==Marriage== In 1973, Dwyer gave up her acting career in order to set up the talent agency Duncan Heath Associates, with her then husband-to-be [[Duncan Heath]],<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0245495/bio Hilary Heath at imdb.com] Retrieved 29 August 2010</ref> now the co-chairman of the Independent Talent Group Ltd. In a 2002 interview in the ''Financial Times'', Heath said of Dwyer "She introduced me to a lot of people - if it wasn't for her it wouldn't have happened."<ref>[http://specials.ft.com/creativebusiness/jan292002/FT3Z198C0XC.html January 2002 article on Duncan Heath at www.ft.com] Retrieved 29 August 2010</ref>
==Producing career==
She began a career as a producer in the mid-1980s under her married name Hilary Heath. She is credited as either Producer or Executive Producer for several movies, including feature films ''[[Criminal Law (film)|Criminal Law]]'' (1989) and ''[[Nil by Mouth (film)|Nil by Mouth]]'' (1997) as well as TV-remakes of [[Daphne du Maurier]]'s ''[[Rebecca (TV miniseries)|Rebecca]]'' (1997) and [[Tennessee Williams]]' ''[[The Roman Spring of Mrs. Stone (2003 film)|The Roman Spring of Mrs. Stone]]'' (2003).<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0245495/ Hilary Heath at imdb.com] Retrieved 29 August 2010</ref>
==Family== Dwyer married [[talent agent]] [[Duncan Heath]] in 1974; they divorced in 1989. They have two children, Laura and Daniel. Laura Heath founded and runs the Hope-Martin Animal Foundation in [[Barbados]].<ref>* [http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/families/article6371953.ece Article on Duncan and Laura Heath in 'Relative Values' in the ''Sunday Times'', 2009] Retrieved 29 August 2010</ref>
